<parameter name="notes">Read DiagramScene.swift (IR + linter), DiagramLayoutSankey.swift (SankeyLayout struct: Node{label,rect,colorIndex,labelCenter}, Link{sourceTop,sourceBottom,targetTop,targetBottom,colorIndex}), and MermaidParser+Sankey.swift (parser: CSV source,target,value lines; nodes in first-appearance order).

Lowering decisions:
- nodes: one Node per SankeyLayout.Node, id=label, frame=rect, isContainer:false (flow bars contain no nodes).
- edges: one Edge per Link. Link stores four band-corner points; I lower to the band centerline [sourceCenter -> targetCenter] where each center is the midpoint of the top/bottom pair at that bar's edge. This gives the linter a real flow route for crossing/occlusion checks. label:nil (sankey links carry no text label in this layout).
- labels: sankey node labels are outboard (labelCenter is beside the bar, NOT centered on it), so they are genuinely free-standing and can collide with adjacent columns' bars/labels — I list them with a synthesized frame from labelCenter (w = label.count*6, h=14). This is the one subtlety: unlike most types where the node's own centered label is implicit, sankey labels sit outside the frame and belong in labels[].

Verified with `swift build` — QuoinCore compiles clean.

Example: a global energy-balance sankey. 22 distinct nodes across ~6 depth columns (primary sources -> carriers -> sectors -> useful/waste energy), 27 weighted links, multiple fan-in/fan-out hubs (Electricity Grid, Industrial Heat, Refined Fuels), long labels ("Electricity Grid", "Road Transport"). Dense enough to stress column stacking, band packing, and outboard-label collisions.